Right now I‚Äôm out of a job but I‚Äôve worked in retail for years in the us. I‚Äôve self disclosed on every application and have got multiple interviews. With the pandemic going on, it‚Äôs been difficult to confirm anything because no one is at work. The thing is, your immediate boss won‚Äôt know if you disclose. At least they shouldn‚Äôt. It‚Äôs more of a corporate thing. So say you have a panic attack at work and your boss has something to say about it, tell them you disclosed on your application and corporate knows about it. Your immediate management isn‚Äôt supposed to know. Like you said, there is still discrimination and ways around it, but if you take it up with a lawyer, the employer will always be wrong.

Um, me? Lol I‚Äôve been hired/interviewed multiple times after self disclosing. I get discriminated against more for being female, honestly. But if it works for you, then that‚Äôs fine! Just wanted to offer my experience.

I personally always self disclose, in case something should go wrong at work, then they can‚Äôt say they didn‚Äôt know I have a panic disorder. I‚Äôm still able to work, I just may have an anxiety attack and if you self disclose employers shouldn‚Äôt be able to fire you over that. If they do, you can take it up with a lawyer. It‚Äôs always good to do research on what the specific laws are for that but they basically can‚Äôt discriminate against you.
